(385, 11, 14, 0, 0, 1, 2, 0, 'SilverStripe\\Lessons\\FAQPage', '2021-01-23 10:29:54', '2020-12-29 17:54:55', NULL, 'Inherit', 'Inherit', 'faq', 'FAQ', NULL, '<p><strong>Q: How much does it cost to get a procedure or appointment?</strong></p><p>A: This depends on your condition, what tests you might require, and what you health insurance policy (if you have this) may cover. Please be in touch with us and we can send out these details.</p><p><a href="https://www.southerncross.co.nz/-/media/Southern-Cross-Health-Society/Health-insurance/Eligibility-criteria/Gastroenterology/colonoscopy-in-adults.pdf?la=en&amp;hash=E0A0921A05E3CA8CD6F1EDB55D6ACC6F45242ED3">Southern Cross Colonoscopy Coverage</a></p><p><strong>Q: How long do I have to wait?</strong></p><p>A: I can accomodate short notice and urgent appointments if required - please let my team know.</p><p><strong>Q: I just want a procedure but not a clinic appointment - is this OK?</strong></p><p>A: Yes, depending on your condition or concerns or what is found a clinic appointment may be necessary to discuss ongoing care. Similarly, sometimes only a clinic is needed and investigations/tests may not be required.</p><p><strong>Q: I don''t have a GP - this is OK?</strong></p><p>A: You can still get in touch and we can start to investigate and sort through the problem. However, a GP is a vital person to continue to have in the loop and be in contact with, particularly if this is a long-term condition.</p><p><strong>Q: My family member has just had a colonoscopy and polyps were found - do I need a colonoscopy?</strong></p><p>A: This depends on a few things including their age, how many polyps were found and what sort they are. Get in touch to discuss this!&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Q: How do I stop developing polyps and colon cancer?</strong></p><p>A: Some things you cannot change. Things that have been studied that can decrease risk include&nbsp;<span><strong>lifestyle risk factors.</strong></span></p><ul><li>A diet high in fat and red or processed meat and low in fibre</li>\n<li>A sedentary lifestyle</li>\n<li>Cigarette smoking</li>\n<li>Alcohol use – heavy use thought to have a very large impact: increase risk of 44% compared with non-drinkers and occasional drinkers</li>\n<li>Obesity&nbsp;</li>\n</ul><p>Modifying these risk factors may help lower your risk of colorectal cancer, in addition to improving your overall health</p><p><a href="[sitetree_link,id=18]">For more information</a></p>', NULL, NULL, 1, 1, 4, 0, 0, NULL, 0),
